    <!-- Legal disclaimer -->
    <string name="legal_title">Before you record</string>
    <string name="legal_intro">Jurisdictions fall into three tiers. Find yours and act accordingly. This is not legal advice.</string>

    <string name="legal_tier1_title">1. No notification required (one-party consent)</string>
    <string name="legal_tier1_summary">Ukraine, UK, federal US + ~38 states, Canada, Australia, Poland.</string>
    <string name="legal_tier1_body">A participant in a conversation may record it without notifying the other party. Your own consent is sufficient. Basis: federal Wiretap Act 18 U.S.C. § 2511 in the US, RIPA 2000 in the UK, Criminal Code § 184(2)(a) in Canada.</string>

    <string name="legal_tier2_title">2. Notification is sufficient (all-party + implied consent)</string>
    <string name="legal_tier2_summary">~11 US states: California, Illinois, Florida, Maryland, and others.</string>
    <string name="legal_tier2_body">Full list: CA (Penal Code § 632), FL, IL, MD, MA, MT, NV, NH, PA, WA, CT. Notify the other party at the start of the call — if they heard it and continued, that is implied consent and recording is legal. The doctrine is established by decades of case law. The same mechanism is used in commercial hotline disclaimers in the EU.</string>

    <string name="legal_tier3_title">3. Prohibited even with notification (explicit consent)</string>
    <string name="legal_tier3_summary">Germany, Austria, Belgium. Explicit consent is required — notification is not legally sufficient.</string>
    <string name="legal_tier3_body">Germany — § 201 StGB Vertraulichkeit des Wortes, up to 3 years in prison for recording "non-publicly spoken words" without explicit permission. German courts do not recognize implied consent in private conversations. Austria — § 120 StGB. Belgium — criminal law + electronic communications, written consent often required. Do not use Ever Call Recorder in these jurisdictions without explicit consent from the other party.</string>

    <string name="legal_tech_title">Ever Call Recorder and beeping the other party</string>
    <string name="legal_tech_body">We technically cannot play a beep or announcement to the other party — that is a system privilege of Pixel Phone, unavailable to third-party apps. A verbal notice at the start of the call works in mode 2 (implied consent). In mode 3 even that is not enough — explicit consent is required.</string>

    <string name="legal_share">Recording ≠ distribution. The user is responsible for publishing without the other party\'s consent — even in one-party jurisdictions.</string>
    <string name="legal_footer">Details and sources — in the project README.</string>
    <string name="legal_action_accept">Understood, continue</string>
    <string name="legal_action_close">Close</string>
    <string name="settings_calibration_done">Reset. The next call will run a new calibration.</string>

